.TH man 3 "19 August 2025" "1.0" "Simple Shell man page"

.SH NAME

Simple Shell \- create a new shell in your terminal.

.SH SYNOPSIS

$ [command_line] [argument_1] ...
.P
(You may first enable the Simple Shell by executing the hsh file : ./hsh)

.SH DESCRIPTION

Simple Shell creates a new shell in your terminal. I can be used like a Linux shell.
.br
As the Simple Shell handle the PATH environment variable, you can use commands by typing their entire path, or simply the command name if they are available in the PATH. 
.br
You can also add arguments to your commands while using the Simple Shell. 
.P
The Simple Shell have a bunch of built-in commands, such as 
.B env 
and 
.B exit.
You can directly type them in your terminal to print your environment variables or exit the Simple Shell.  
.P
To exit the Simple Shell, you can either use 
.B exit 
or the command 
.B Ctrl+D.

.SH RETURN VALUE

Simple Shell returns 0 when it exits with success, or 1 when an error occurs. 

.SH EXAMPLES

Output examples :

.P 
$ ls
.br
file_1 file_2 file_3
.br
$ /bin/ls -l
.br
-rw-r--r-- 1 John John     8 Aug 18 16:20 file_1
.br
-rwxr-xr-x 1 John John 17888 Aug 19 11:03 file_2
.br
-rw-r--r-- 1 John John  4221 Aug 19 11:03 file_3

